{{compu-AI-stub}}

A '''quantum bus''' is a device which can be used to store or transfer information between independent [[qubits]] in a [[quantum computer]], or combine two qubits into a [[Superposition principle|superposition]]. It is the [[Quantum mechanics|quantum]] analog of a [[Bus (computing)|classical bus]].
==History== The concept was first demonstrated by researchers at [[Yale University]] and the [[National Institute of Standards and Technology]] (NIST) in 2007.<ref>{{cite journal|author=J. Majer |author2=[[J. M. Chow]] |author3=J. M. Gambetta |author4=Jens Koch |author5=B. R. Johnson |author6=J. A. Schreier |author7=L. Frunzio |author8=D. I. Schuster |author9=A. A. Houck |author10=[[A. Wallraff]] |author11=A. Blais |author12=[[M. H. Devoret]] |author13=[[S. M. Girvin]] |author14=[[R. J. Schoelkopf]] |title=Coupling superconducting qubits via a cavity bus|date=2007-09-27|journal=Nature|volume=449|pages=443–447|doi=10.1038/nature06184|arxiv=0709.2135|pmid=17898763|issue=7161|bibcode = 2007Natur.449..443M }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author=M. A. Sillanpää|author2=J. I. Park |author3=R. W. Simmonds |title=Coherent quantum state storage and transfer between two phase qubits via a resonant cavity|journal=Nature|volume=449|pages=438–42|date=2007-09-27|doi=10.1038/nature06124|pmid=17898762|issue=7161|bibcode = 2007Natur.449..438S |arxiv = 0709.2341 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.photonics.com/Article.aspx?AID=30972|title=All Aboard the Quantum 'Bus'|accessdate=2008-12-12|date=2007-09-27}}</ref> Prior to this experimental demonstration, the quantum bus had been described by scientists at [[NIST]] as one of the possible cornerstone building blocks in [[quantum computing]] architectures.<ref>{{cite journal|author=G.K. Brennen |author2=D. Song |author3=C.J. Williams|title=Quantum-computer architecture using nonlocal interactions|journal=Physical Review A|volume=67|year=2003|arxiv=quant-ph/0301012|issue=5|doi=10.1103/PhysRevA.67.050302|pages=050302|bibcode = 2003PhRvA..67e0302B }}</ref>
== Mathematical Description == A quantum bus for [[Superconducting quantum computing|superconducting qubits]] can be built with a [[resonance cavity]]. The [[Hamiltonian (quantum mechanics)|hamiltonian]] for a system with qubit A, qubit B, and the resonance cavity or quantum bus connecting the two is <math>\hat{H}=\hat{H}_r+\sum\limits_{j=A,B} \hat{H}_j +\sum\limits_{j=A,B}hg_i\left(\hat{a}^\dagger\hat{\sigma}^j_-+\hat{a}\hat{\sigma}^j_{\text{+}}\right)</math> where <math>\hat{H} = \frac{1}{2}\hbar\omega_j\hat{\sigma}^j_+\hat{\sigma}^j_-</math> is the single qubit hamiltonian, <math>\hat{\sigma}^j_+\hat{\sigma}^j_-</math> is the raising or lowering operator for creating or destroying excitations in the <math>j</math>th qubit, and <math>\hbar\omega_j</math> is controlled by the amplitude of the [[Direct current|D.C.]] and [[radio frequency]] [[flux]] bias.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sillanpää|first=Mika A.|last2=Park|first2=Jae I.|last3=Simmonds|first3=Raymond W.|title=Coherent quantum state storage and transfer between two phase qubits via a resonant cavity|url=http://www.nature.com/doifinder/10.1038/nature06124|journal=Nature|volume=449|issue=7161|pages=438–442|doi=10.1038/nature06124|arxiv=0709.2341|bibcode=2007Natur.449..438S}}</ref>
